{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06c53251-e0d2-47f5-bb6a-583db2596fe6","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it has no effect. Here's what you actually need:\n\n### iOS — opt out of safe-area insets\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### Android — transparent system bars\nIn your `MainActivity.cs` (or a lifecycle handler):\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nWindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nWindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\nOn Android 15+ (API 35), apps are edge-to-edge by default, but the bars may still have a scrim — setting them transparent removes it.\n\n### Hide the navigation chrome\nIf you're inside a `Shell` or `NavigationPage`, also hide its toolbar:\n\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n<!-- or -->\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n```\n\n### Minimal full-screen photo page\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Replace `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` with `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`, make Android system bars transparent, and hide any navigation bar.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1e2535d2-2ab2-4b42-88d0-bafa43f920ad","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is building a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is not actually a property on ContentPage in .NET MAUI. The user might be confusing it with something else.\n\n2. In .NET MAUI, to go edge-to-edge, you typically need to:\n   - On Android: Use `Window.SetStatusBarColor` or configure the activity to be full-screen\n   - On iOS: Deal with safe area insets\n\nActually, the key property I should focus on is `IgnoreSafeArea`. On iOS, views respect safe areas by default, so setting `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the image or its container should allow it to extend behind the status bar and navigation bar. For Android, I'd need to handle the platform-specific configuration separately.\n\nSetting up the MAUI layout... I need to clarify the right approach here. For iOS, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the correct platform-specific property to extend content edge-to-edge, while Android requires making the status and navigation bars transparent and handling the edge-to-edge display separately. The `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` property the user mentioned isn't the right solution for this scenario.","outputTokens":1481,"requestId":"4828:3A5014:5515DB6:5D512E0:69F3FD7A"},"id":"7fee9ad1-57b8-4c8d-9fd9-49d37e723940","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:10:44.708Z","parentId":"a796cebf-b5f6-4baf-b41d-6351cdf11af2"}
